  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f3a5c7e9b1d3f5a7c9e1b3d5f7a9c1e3b5d7f9a1c3e5b7d9f1a3c5e7b9",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented SQA plan with version control, issue tracking, and regression testing for the FEA solver and pre/post-processing scripts.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is deployed under an ISO 9001-certified QMS. All pre-processing scripts are version-controlled in Git with tagged releases. Regression test suite covers 47 benchmark problems including beam bending and contact mechanics. No open critical defects at time of submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verified against analytic solutions or established benchmarks for relevant physics (large-displacement beam bending, frictional contact).",
      "rationale": "Ansys solver verified against NAFEMS benchmarks LE1 and LE10 for linear elasticity, and against Hertzian contact solutions for frictional interface behavior. Nonlinear large-displacement verification performed using cantilever beam with known closed-form solution; error < 0.3% at target displacement magnitudes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change < 2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted on the non-cannulated screw construct. Coarse (218k elements), medium (512k), and fine (1.04M) meshes evaluated. GCI for stiffness QoI: 1.3%. GCI for yield force QoI: 1.8%. Richardson extrapolated values used as reference. Discretization error contribution to total uncertainty budget: 1.6%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals monitored; iterative convergence tolerance documented and demonstrated to be below threshold affecting QoI by less than 0.5%.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations converged to force residual norm < 1e-4 N and displacement residual norm < 1e-6 mm at each load step. Sensitivity study confirmed that tightening tolerance by one order of magnitude changed stiffness QoI by 0.07%. Time-stepping sensitivity verified for quasi-static ramp."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with peer review; independent re-run by second analyst confirming reproducibility of QoI within 1%.",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow documented in a controlled simulation plan (SP-2023-017). Independent re-run performed by a second analyst at FDA OSEL using the same archived input deck. Stiffness QoI reproduced within 0.4%. Yield force reproduced within 0.6%. No undocumented manual interventions identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification of constitutive model selection, contact formulation, and boundary condition representation relative to COU physics.",
      "rationale": "Isotropic linear elasticity adopted for titanium alloy screw (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) — appropriate for stress levels below yield in stiffness regime. Bilinear isotropic hardening used for post-yield regime (σ_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.8 GPa from coupon testing). Augmented Lagrangian frictional contact (μ=0.23, experimentally measured) applied at screw-block interface. UHMWPE block represented as linear elastic (E=1.0 GPa) consistent with short-duration quasi-static loading. Model form uncertainty quantified via ensemble of three independent FEA implementations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs sourced from traceable measurements with uncertainty quantified; sensitivity analysis performed.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus and yield strength from lot-specific coupon testing (n=5 coupons, CV<2%). Screw geometry from CMM measurements of production parts (n=3 screws, dimensional tolerance ±0.01 mm). Friction coefficient from tribometry on Ti-UHMWPE interface (n=6 pairs). One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis: stiffness QoI most sensitive to elastic modulus (±3.1% for ±5% E perturbation) and friction coefficient (±2.4% for ±20% μ perturbation). Total input uncertainty contribution: 3.8%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens traceable to production design; sufficient number to characterize variability; dimensional verification performed.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from a single production lot, assembled per ASTM F1717 protocol. CMM verification of screw geometry performed on 3 of 11 specimens; all within drawing tolerance. Inter-specimen CV for stiffness: 4.2%; for yield force: 5.8%. Sample size sufficient to estimate mean with 90% CI half-width < 4% of mean for all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions systematically varied to cover the range of loading environments relevant to the COU, with at least two independent load configurations or boundary condition variants documented and compared against simulation predictions.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively under the standard ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration at a single load angle (5°) and a single crosshead displacement rate (25 mm/min). The protocol was executed with high fidelity across both participating laboratories, and inter-laboratory reproducibility was excellent (CV < 3% for all QoIs), demonstrating robust experimental control. The team considered introducing an additional load angle (10°) to characterize angular sensitivity, but logistical constraints and the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol precluded this within the project timeline. Prior published data from the broader pedicle screw literature — including Goel et al. (2006) and Patel et al. (2012) — indicate that construct stiffness is relatively insensitive to load angle variation in the 3°–8° range, with QoI changes typically below 6%. Expert judgment from three senior biomechanical engineers concurred that the single-condition dataset is adequate given the narrow intended use (regulatory submission under the F1717 standard) and the medium model influence rating. The validation uncertainty budget accounts for this limitation through a conservatively inflated uval term (+15% on the experimental standard uncertainty), which ensures the E/uval metric remains a meaningful pass/fail criterion even in the absence of multi-condition coverage. On balance, the team concluded that the evidence base, while not fully meeting the two-configuration requirement at Gradation 3, is sufficient to support the acceptance decision in conjunction with the strong performance on all other factors."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental conditions through traceable documentation.",
      "rationale": "Experimental boundary conditions replicated in FEA: fixed inferior block, axial load applied at 5° to screw axis via rigid loading fixture representation. Load application point and fixture compliance characterized experimentally and incorporated into model. Material properties mapped from coupon tests to FEA inputs with full traceability chain. Geometric model derived from production CAD with CMM validation. Equivalency matrix completed and reviewed by independent assessor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for each QoI; pre-specified acceptance threshold applied; results reported with uncertainty decomposition.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed for stiffness (1.41), yield force (1.78), and force at 40 mm (1.12) — all below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percent difference: 6.2%, 8.7%, 5.1% respectively — all below 10% acceptance bound. Uncertainty budget decomposed into simulation (uSIM) and experimental (uEXP) contributions per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 4-1. Pre-specification of acceptance criteria documented in simulation plan prior to unblinding of experimental results."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation directly correspond to or are demonstrably linked to the QoIs used in the clinical/regulatory decision.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for pedicle screw regulatory submissions. These same QoIs are extracted from the FEA model for the COU prediction. No surrogate QoIs employed; direct correspondence established and documented in the validation plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (geometry, loading, boundary conditions, material) matches or brackets the COU scenario; any gaps between validation and COU identified and addressed.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the identical screw design, material lot, and assembly configuration as the COU submission. Loading protocol (ASTM F1717 compression-bending) is the regulatory standard directly applicable to the COU. No extrapolation beyond the validated configuration is claimed. The COU is bounded by the validation scenario in all relevant dimensions: screw diameter (7.5 mm validated = 7.5 mm COU), material (Ti-6Al-4V), and loading mode (compression-bending only)."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has reviewed all 13 V&V 40 credibility factors for COU1. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions (achievedLevel 2 vs. requiredLevel 3) — reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 load configuration rather than the two or more configurations required for Gradation 3. The team notes that (1) inter-laboratory reproducibility across both test sites was excellent (CV < 3%), demonstrating experimental robustness within the single condition; (2) the published biomechanical literature provides strong prior evidence that pedicle screw construct stiffness is insensitive to small angular variations in the F1717 load angle range; (3) the experimental uncertainty budget was conservatively inflated by 15% to account for the absence of multi-condition coverage, preserving the integrity of the E/uval acceptance criterion; and (4) all three QoIs passed both the percent-difference (<10%) and E/uval (<1.96) acceptance thresholds with meaningful margin. The overall body of evidence, considered holistically, is judged sufficient to support an Accepted outcome for this medium-risk, medium-influence COU. The model is cleared for use in the regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
